---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import Nav from '../../components/Nav.astro';
import Footer from '../../components/Footer.astro';
---

<Base
  title="Crontinel vs Datadog for Laravel Queue Monitoring"
  description="Datadog can monitor Laravel queues, but it takes StatsD setup, custom metrics, and hand-built dashboards. Crontinel works out of the box with zero configuration."
>
  <Nav />

  <main class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 py-16">

    <div class="text-center mb-14">
      <div class="inline-block text-xs font-semibold text-gray-400 bg-gray-800 border border-gray-700 px-3 py-1 rounded-full mb-4">
        Crontinel vs Datadog
      </div>
      <h1 class="text-3xl sm:text-4xl font-bold text-white mb-4">
        Datadog can do it.<br class="hidden sm:block" /> Crontinel does it <em class="text-green-400 not-italic">without the setup.</em>
      </h1>
      <p class="text-gray-400 max-w-xl mx-auto">
        Datadog is a powerful full-stack observability platform. It can technically monitor Laravel queue depth and Horizon metrics, but only after you wire up DogStatsD, emit custom metrics, build dashboards, and configure monitors by hand. Crontinel ships with all of that built in.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="space-y-8 mb-16">

      <div class="bg-gray-900 border border-gray-800 rounded-xl p-6">
        <h2 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-2">What Datadog does well</h2>
        <p class="text-gray-400">
          Datadog is the industry standard for infrastructure and application observability at scale: APM, distributed tracing, log management, synthetic monitors, dashboards. It covers a lot of ground. If your organization already runs Datadog, it's a serious tool with serious capabilities.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-gray-900 border border-gray-800 rounded-xl p-6">
        <h2 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-2">The Laravel queue monitoring gap</h2>
        <p class="text-gray-400 mb-4">
          Datadog doesn't understand Horizon out of the box. To get queue depth alerts, you need to instrument your app to emit custom metrics via DogStatsD, set up a StatsD agent, create a Datadog monitor, and build a dashboard. It's all possible, but it's a multi-day project, not a two-command install.
        </p>
        <div class="bg-gray-950 rounded-lg p-4 font-mono text-xs text-gray-400 space-y-1">
          <div><span class="text-yellow-400">step 1</span> Install and configure DogStatsD agent on each server</div>
          <div><span class="text-yellow-400">step 2</span> Emit custom metrics from your Laravel app code</div>
          <div><span class="text-yellow-400">step 3</span> Create a Datadog monitor with custom thresholds</div>
          <div><span class="text-yellow-400">step 4</span> Build a dashboard for queue and Horizon state</div>
          <div><span class="text-yellow-400">step 5</span> Configure alert routing and notification channels</div>
          <div class="pt-1 border-t border-gray-800 mt-1"></div>
          <div class="text-gray-500">...repeat for every new project</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-gray-900 border border-gray-800 rounded-xl p-6">
        <h2 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-2">Crontinel: zero configuration</h2>
        <p class="text-gray-400 mb-4">
          Crontinel reads Horizon's Redis state directly. No custom metrics, no agents, no dashboards to build. Install the package and you get queue depth, supervisor status, failed job rate, and scheduler run history, all wired up with sensible defaults.
        </p>
        <div class="bg-gray-950 rounded-lg p-4 font-mono text-xs space-y-1">
          <div><span class="text-green-400">✓</span> <span class="text-green-400">composer require crontinel/laravel</span></div>
          <div><span class="text-green-400">✓</span> <span class="text-green-400">php artisan crontinel:install</span></div>
          <div class="pt-1 border-t border-gray-800 mt-1"></div>
          <div><span class="text-green-400">✓</span> Horizon supervisor monitoring: active</div>
          <div><span class="text-green-400">✓</span> Queue depth tracking: active</div>
          <div><span class="text-green-400">✓</span> Scheduled job history: active</div>
          <div><span class="text-green-400">✓</span> Slack alerts: configured</div>
        </div>
      </div>

    </div>

    <div class="overflow-x-auto mb-16">
      <table class="w-full text-sm">
        <thead>
          <tr class="border-b border-gray-800 text-left">
            <th class="pb-3 text-gray-400 font-medium">Capability</th>
            <th class="pb-3 text-gray-400 font-medium text-center">Crontinel</th>
            <th class="pb-3 text-gray-400 font-medium text-center">Datadog</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody class="divide-y divide-gray-800/50">
          {[
            ['Horizon queue monitoring out of the box', true, false],
            ['Zero custom metric instrumentation needed', true, false],
            ['No agents or DogStatsD required', true, false],
            ['Horizon supervisor paused detection', true, false],
            ['Per-queue depth and oldest job age', true, false],
            ['Scheduled job run history (auto-recorded)', true, false],
            ['Failed jobs per minute with alerting', true, false],
            ['Full-stack APM and distributed tracing', false, true],
            ['Infrastructure metrics (CPU, memory, disk)', false, true],
            ['Log management at scale', false, true],
            ['Custom dashboards and metrics', false, true],
            ['Slack / email alerts', true, true],
            ['Open source / self-hostable', true, false],
            ['Pricing suitable for small and mid teams', true, false],
          ].map(([cap, ours, theirs]) => (
            <tr>
              <td class="py-3 text-gray-300">{cap}</td>
              <td class="py-3 text-center">{ours ? <span class="text-green-400">✓</span> : <span class="text-red-400">✗</span>}</td>
              <td class="py-3 text-center">{theirs ? <span class="text-green-400">✓</span> : <span class="text-red-400">✗</span>}</td>
            </tr>
          ))}
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-gray-900 border border-gray-800 rounded-xl p-6 mb-8">
      <h2 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-2">When Datadog makes sense, and when it doesn't</h2>
      <p class="text-gray-400">
        If you're a large engineering team with dedicated DevOps and a need for full-stack observability across dozens of services, Datadog earns its price. If you're a Laravel team that wants queue health and scheduler alerting without a platform migration, Crontinel gets you there in minutes instead of days, at a fraction of the cost.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-gray-900 border border-green-500/20 rounded-xl p-8 text-center">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-white mb-2">Purpose-built for Laravel. Ready in minutes.</h2>
      <p class="text-gray-400 mb-6">
        No agents. No custom metrics. No dashboards to build. Two commands and you're monitoring.
      </p>
      <div class="relative max-w-sm mx-auto mb-6">
        <div class="bg-gray-950 rounded-lg p-4 pr-14 font-mono text-sm text-green-400 text-left">
          <div>composer require crontinel/laravel</div>
          <div>php artisan crontinel:install</div>
        </div>
        <button onclick="navigator.clipboard.writeText('composer require crontinel/laravel\nphp artisan crontinel:install'); this.textContent='Copied!'; setTimeout(()=>this.textContent='Copy',1500)" class="absolute top-2 right-2 text-xs text-gray-500 hover:text-gray-300 bg-gray-800 hover:bg-gray-700 px-2 py-1 rounded transition-colors">Copy</button>
      </div>
      <a
        href="/#waitlist"
        class="inline-block bg-green-500 hover:bg-green-400 text-black font-semibold px-6 py-2.5 rounded transition-colors"
      >
        Start free
      </a>
    </div>

  </main>

  <Footer />
</Base>
